x4freetext: Angular distribution of
neutrons from D(t,n)He-4 reaction was evaluated from
curves given by N.Jarmie and J.D.Seagrave.
Van De Graaff generator, producing
a 4 uA beam of 4.2 MeV deuterons.
Air cooled titanium-tritium disk target 1 mg/cm2
thick, various neutron angles used to obtain
different energies.
All samples were cylinders of spectroscopically pure
elements of diameter 10.5 mm and length 49.5 mm.
Eight such samples used spaced at 20 deg intervals.
Eight samples were irradiated simultaneously
in all cases except silicon. In silicon measurement
only one sample was irradiated at time.
Sample  Irradiation time Waiting time Counting time
Al         9.75 h          > 27min         5min
Mg        12.3 h           > 45 min        5min
Si         5 min             1 min         5min
Co *        2.0 h          > 40 min        5min
Co **      12.25 h         > 48 min       variable
Ni         11.5 h          > 30 min       variable
* - for n,alpha reaction,
** - for  n,2n and n,p reactions.
Background measured with unirradiated sample in
rotation at frequent intervals was found to be less
few percents of counts under photopeak.
NaI(Tl) well crystal, 4.4 cm by 5.1 cm, with
a cylindrical well 1.3 cm in diameter and
4.01 cm deep. For samples counting.
Before counting the samples were placed in plexiglass
holder also served to absorb a part of unwanted beta
activity, that accompanies the gamma rays.
Empirical measure of "effective" efficiency of crystal
for the irradiated sources was described in Appendix
of reference.
Entire spectrometer was surrounded by 5 cm lead to
reduce background.
Plastic scintillator used as proton recoil
spectrometer. Scintillator was 2.0 cm in
diameter, 1.0 cm thick, mounted on an EMI
6097 photomultiplier and placed at 50 cm
from the target at 90 deg to beam direction.
Photopeaks were assumed to have Gaussian shape,
Compton tails with backgrounds were amused to be
given by series of exponential.
Area under photo peak was evaluated and standard
errors were obtained by inverting the normal matrix.
Data from publication.
For background.
